Zordon looks like one of those toys where you stick your hand into some pins and it makes an impression.  Honestly, I think Patrick Stewart would have been a better Zordon. (In terms of voice.)  Okay, Alpha 5 doesn't look as bad as the photos and the toy, but Bill Hader's voice sounds kind of off.  I take it Trini's parents are either overprotective or Trini had a drug problem in the past.  Okay, seeing the Rangers in the suits, fighting putties, is pretty awesome!  I don't care what people think, I think the Zords look pretty cool!  Don't know about the Megazord yet though... text: I already know exactly what the problem is gonna be with this whole film; it won't be the cgi, the story, or the acting. It's the fact that there won't be any tension. I figured it out as soon as I saw that one Ranger say "that's a lotta gold" at 1:58. If there's a giant supernatural monster killing people and destroying a town, are you going to be smiling and making jokes about it as it happens? No, you won't, especially if you're one of the people trying to save lives. They're throwing lines like that in out of nowhere in an effort to make seem like it a fun, quippy action blockbuster, but up until that point the film instead seemed like it was going to be a gritty real-world take on the Power Rangers story. I hope it's good, but this trailer lowered my expectations.

text: The way I see it is, we still don't know 100% until the movie comes out. Anything can happen in the meantime. Reshoots, added or removed scenes, more time to perfect the special effects, and other marketing efforts. As for the Rangers, I personally saw much better interaction this time around compared to the 1st trailer. Not too happy with Alpha's design, and I wish they'd enhanced Zordon's voice to give it more ethereal, alienistic quality. Goldar's design doesnt look very original or amazing, and I wonder if he will retain any of his personality from the original show. Finally, I actually don't mind the Rangers having super powers, as I believe Dino Thunder actually did this with their Rangers (and fun tie in: Tommy, the original green ranger- and later on, gold ranger and red ranger- was in that season). So, who knows what else they're going to do with this. I'm nervous but at the same time the only thing I'll be losing is some time and money, as I still have the original series to go back to.

This film promises to ground the Power Rangers in the real world and not some Saved by the Bell studio backlot.  Not only does it have an interesting new look but it still feels like the Power Rangers.  There's genuine humor, there's exciting action, and the effects are definitely a welcome upgrade.  They've even improved a few story things (for instance, they're actually showing us that these kids have families, which makes a lot more sense than what they did in the originals).  Overall, very excited to see this new rendition now.  Just... DON'T LET ME DOWN, MOVIE!

text: Imagine if an adaptation we all love, say Game of Thrones or the Lord of the Rings films (which I understand have inaccuracies, but not enough to derail many fans of the original books) had as much in common with their original books as this trailer has in common with the original Power Rangers series. We would all be furious.  This looks like the writers or studio or whatever were told to make a Power Rangers film, so they read the first few pages of the wikipedia page and then wrote the script. Now matter what kind of reviews this movie ends up getting, it's shameful to call this a Power Rangers adaptation.  For fans of the old series looking for a more faithful modern adaptation, I would recommend the Power Rangers comics from Boom! studios. It has much of what we loved about the TV series, but is written well enough that adults who loved the series as kids can enjoy it.

text: Okay a lot of people are complaining about how different this looks compared to the original series.¬† And a lot of people are responding that those fans need to understand that changes have to happen.¬† That the show was cheesy and the characters were just bland stereotypes.¬† There is some truth to those statements I‚Äôm not denying that BUT this is just substituting one form of stereotype for another.¬† We‚Äôve gone from five idealistic do-gooders to five angsty emos who look like they just came from Fan4stic.¬† Rita Repulsa is still the on-note world-conqueror just in a skimpy outfit.¬† Though the worst part are the zords and henchmen.¬† In the case of the former their redesign makes them look like Michael Bay‚Äôs Transformers.¬† And in the latter they‚Äôve taken some fairly uniquely designed villains from the original like Goldar and the Putties and turned them into interchangeable generic monsters.¬† The crowning cherry of crap here though is the rap music.¬† Because the last time someone mixed rap with Power Rangers it worked so well.¬† The only update that seems to work is the revamped Zordon and the Ranger‚Äôs suits which look very impressive.

So if this film doesn't reliever acting wise or even story wise... it's not that big of a deal. text: Top wins shown so far: 1. Realistic armor and circuits in the suits give the Rangers more credibility. I would take those Rangers more seriously than the spandex wearing ones any day. 2. The fact that Rita appears in the Yellow Ranger's home shows that the Villains know the Rangers' true identities, providing an actual serious threat compared to the bumbling idiotic Rita in the original TV show. 3. All design complaints about the Zords aside, they are shown to fire actual ammunition compared to the typical 90s fantasy lasers in the original series. Again, bonus points for reality based weaponry. 4. Those Putties actually look like they are made out of rocks this time. 5. A bit of actual Zord piloting is shown to be done by the Rangers compared to the lazy "voice command" piloting style of the original Rangers. Always a win for the attention to detail. -And that, folks, is why i have faith in this movie. Just my thoughts, take it easy.

text: I see comments of people not taking the reboot well. If you don't want to count it as canon, then don't. Just give the movie a fair chance. And in all reality, the Mighty Morphin Power Rangers are an alternation of the Super Sentai, the ORIGINAL series. Power Rangers is basically the Americanized version of it, because it's a live action show and dubbing is for animation. In all of the scenes where you see characters in the flesh, that's the reenactment, in the scenes where they're in their transformed states, it's dubbed to the suitable audience. That's my theory, at least. But back on topic, to those complaining that this movie will 'ruin their childhood', you don't have to count this movie as canon, as the original Power Rangers is basically a different continuity than the source material. Did you know that there's Super Sentai series BEFORE the one that was converted to MMPR that were never reenacted and dubbed?

text: Man, I think I MIGHT actually like this. I mean, I remember hearing about this new show called "Power Rangers" as a kid and having my mind jump to a bunch of super powered park rangers, but then I saw that first episode and lost my mind.   So I'm biased.   But hey, it's all there; a group of five teenagers wind up with Zordon (and nightmare inducing Alpha 5), get turned into the power rangers, kick the crap out of some Puttys (decent martial arts too), Rita Repulsa makes her monster grow (couldn't resist), the Zords show up, actually DO something against Goldar (get their asses kicked it looks like), then form the Megazord, and doubtless kick the crap out of him. It's the first episode in big budget movie form, with a heavy lean on the alien angle.  I'm in. I was on the fence for a long time, but I'm in.  But Rita had BETTER come from a space-dumpster! (I kid)

It brings to mind Star Trek original series. Mega morphing cheese factor. However! All of that considered, this trailer looks really good for a "power rangers" movie trailer. It looks like it has a decent story, lots of action, and honestly would it be a power rangers movie without at least a little cheese in there. I'm willing to give it a chance to see if it's any good. text: As much as I liked the original power rangers as a kid, looking back, the show was always cheesy. The actors were dorky, the acting was hilarious, the enemies were silly, but the watching a bunch of normal teens kung fu-ing bad guys in colorful super spandex never got old and seeing megazord transform and fight was magical. I wasn't sold on the film before, but I feel like this trailer captures and updates a lot of what the original was about, and I only hope kids will enjoy it the way I did.  Let's not pretend the original show was an untouchable masterpiece and should not be remade. Aliens, or Robocop, or Terminator are classic films by masters that shouldn't be remade, but anyone thinking the same applies to Power Rangers is delusional.

text: The state of the modern film industry completely ruins any aesthetic the franchise ever had. The actors will spend virtually the entire movie out of their suits or with their helmets "open" because basically nobody will agree to keep their face covered in a new movie, as if tanks their marketability (unless they're already famous like Ryan Reynolds). They made Rita all sexy instead of an old crone, because God forbid we have a female character that doesn't revolve around her ass.  They made the suits look sleek and "modern" instead of keeping their iconic bulky look, and the Zords look like Transformers rejects.  The voice for Zordon sucks, too. The VA for the 1995 movie is still alive, why didn't the get him? Oh yeah, right. Modern movies need A-list celebrities to fill up the movie poster. Garbage.

text: this movie is gonna be awesome, now before any of you haters start attacking me hear me out. 1. yes this movie's taking itself to a darker tone than the show, but the show was cheezy and silly, think of batman at first he was the silliest and cheeziest superhero anyone ever knew, well what happened? he grew dark and now he's one of the greatest superheroes of all time. 2. the suits actually look impressive, the spandex suits just wouldn't work for this darker toned power rangers, and besides what good is spandex gonna do against knives and bullets? if they do get into a knife and gunfight anyway. 3. most of the movie's designs look pretty cool, and I'll be honest here I really don't like alpha 5's design he looks like crap. OK but seeing them in motion is a bigger difference than seeing them in a picture or poster. 4. all the characters so far seem to be really likable. 5. yes it's an unknown cast, but not all the cast is unknown and they really seem to care for the project and had lots of fun doing it. that's all I had to say.

text: I want to know who in the world invented these technicolor coded heroes, and how far back do I have to time travel to make sure this never becomes a thing. I mean WHERE in the history of great warriors in this world was this ever a thing. And I only mean the 5 man or 6 man teams where each color is symbolic of your personality. I get the concept was designed for children to help differentiate each character, but this is 2017. Maybe the red ranger or the alpha of the team, is actually female. The pink ranger could have been a dude, or maybe a gay ranger in the mix. What color is the gay ranger? Depends what shoes he's wearing. And you know whoever's not in red or blue is usually the funny one also known as the least favorite of the bunch. Why cant the clown be the alpha? Cause that's not funny. This assorted arrangement was meant for comic books, but today it's stereotyping in technicolor. I know some of you grew up with this thing, as did I, but to a kid with a group of friends, out on Halloween...who gets to wear the cool blue and red costumes? and who gets stuck with yellow or green or purple? Who wants to be THAT guy???. Of course they were very careful with the casting in this movie. God forbid the black ranger be a black guy, or the yellow ranger be the asian guy, but it's ok to make the yellow and pink ranger both female, cause those are girl colors, so they have to be. The Power Rangers were a QUICK fad from 1993-1997. So realistically Power Rangers were HUGE for a good 2-4yrs for the people born from around 1986 to 1994. That is a small window of fanbase to make a Hollywood big budget movie in 2017.  The people that are currently under 23 years old will never remember when Power Rangers were GOOD!! text: I had doubts about this movie when it first announced, and now I see why my gut had doubts. The first bad thing they did was give a release date with absolutely nothing to back it behind. Seriously, even Michael Bay wouldn't do something that stupid. The second stupid thing they did was hire Zack Stentz and Ashley Miller, the two writing hacks behind the Transformers and Star Trek films. I honestly think these two don't even bother researching the source material for the films they make, instead they just shit out whatever they come with. Because of them, the movie took WAY too many liberties to where the personalities of the characters don't match the real Power Ranger characters, nor does it match the real Power Rangers origin story. Yes, I can accept SOME changes to a new adaptation (I did that with the Chris Nolan Batman trilogy), but I can't accept characters who do something out of character. You've never seen Jason pranking a rival high school team then have the cops come after him, you've never seen any of the other rangers be portrayed as angsty (or "screw ups" as they call themselves), and you've never heard Zordon tell the rangers they're unworthy to be Power Rangers. FYI, I have nothing against the cast, because they can only work with what they're given, and that's not their fault. However, they could research the character they were portraying to help get into character. The next stupid thing they did was hire Dean Israelite as the director, even though most of his films are half-assed, because they often get 5 or 6 out of 10 stars (look up his directing credits on IMDB).  I'll admit I was excited to see this movie after watching this trailer, because it changed my views on if it would be good or not. It made me think that this would be not only a fresh take, but a good take, on the franchise. Now all of that excitement went down the shitter after seeing this piece of shit all of the way through on opening night. I walked out of that theater feeling insulted, and was shocked to realize what I saw was not a Power Rangers movie. Ever since I got home that night, and up until now, I've been getting my thoughts down on paper for a fan-film reboot as a way to make up for this film. I shouldn't have to reboot this "reboot", but no, Shat Stentz and Ass-ley Miller made me feel a need to do this, because like the typical leeches that they are, they clearly don't respect franchises like this one. And just so you're aware, this fan-film will have some changes as well, but it will still relate itself to the source material at the same time.

text: this is a awesome movie. i was a little nervous going into this movie. i did not want the film makers to mess up my childhood show. but i was very impressed with the movie. they did not change too much, they did change the characteristics of some of the rangers but not too much the one that was portrayed very well was billy the blue ranger and rita was done very well as well. ok here are some spoilers do not continue to read if you don't want to know. one thing i really liked about it was that they did not know each other and you see the friendship grow, you get to see the bacground of the rangers and their personal lives. you see them meet for the first time and see the friendship grow, you see them train, having trouble morphing, using the zords and so on. they are not told by zordon on how to do stuff but learn on their own. u see the history of zordon and rita. you know how in the show they mention that zordon was a ranger well you see that in this movie. and there is some homage to the film like, it's morphing time, alpha says his catch phrase and when you see all the dino zords running in a montage the theme song plays. i was highly satisfied with this movie they changed it a little bit but kept true to what the power rangers are and the costumes were awesome. goldar was even cool. the acting was good, the story was good and the special effects are good. and the zords were sweet. can't wait for the sequel. make sure you watch after the credits. if you have not seen this movie then i recommend you do and the putties were well made as well rating 5/5

text: This movie was good. Granted it has its flaws. We don't see the "Power Rangers" till the climax and even then they only have one fight scene before they got in their Zords and I didn't really like Elizabeth Banks as Rita Repulsa. A little weird in her talking and was kinda over the top but not in the fun way likemthe original Rita. The Rangers themselves were likable though some more than others. text: I remember seeing a commercial on TV for the pilot of¬†series, when this show first came out the U.S. (I think that it was '93) and thinking "This show won't last more than a few episodes". It just looked so AWEFUL. The costumes and make-up for the villains were laughably cheap, the acting was WAY over the top (especially for the villains), the dialogue was cheesy beyond belief, and the girl rangers actually wore SKIRTS! When was the last time that you¬†saw a female soldier wearing a skirt into combat? It was like watching an extremely low budget 1950s/early 1960s Godzilla movie crossed with Plan 9 From Outer Space. Which isn't to say that it couldn't have been great as an animated show. Needless to say, I never watched the series; but this movie actually looks really good! I've heard a lot of really good reviews about it; and they say that about the first 2/3rds of it¬†consist of really good¬†character-development. Well, except for the part about one of the male Rangers briefly accidentally giving a bull a hand-job (apparently, he couldn't tell a male from a female). I think that I'll go see it.

text: REVIEW, NO SPOILERS.  This movie was good at first, it wasn't as cliche as I thought it would be at the start.  I mean, sure, you kinda have your cliche school children 'group', but that's what the original power rangers was like.   Aside from the start - it became almost too predictable, oh, this is about to happen? Well, I know what'll happen next. It was literally like that, it was comedy more than anything. You're also dealing with too much cheesy story line, sure, the actors were okay with this type of movie but the story line was the huge problem.  It was like watching Dora asking you where the most obvious thing is, yeah, it's that painful.   I do believe they aimed this at the wrong audience, felt like for kids, but not for kids(?) I don't know what that's all about, the "Billy" of the group fitted in perfectly, and he was probably my favourite character of them all, because he fit in his role well and he did a good job with it.  I'd give this movie a 4/10 and that's at a stretch, I would've gotten my money back if I could, obviously point of views are a thing w/ opinions, so don't take my word for it, look at other reviews and check out some clips to note your decision down compared to mine.   Thanks.

text: Okay so before you watch this, there are some issues. This won't contain spoilers. First of all Power Rangers 2017 is nothing like gen 1 90's PR. This is actually a good thing, means it isn't super cheesy. Other good things include the fact that the baddies no longer double as comic relief. It's also a good movie which doesn't milk the past too much.   Now the bad, and rising above all else is the fact that the rangers don't morph until the final 30 mins of the movie, which is just too late. There is little time, so we see 30 secs of fighting in armour before we jump straight to the zords. Speaking of the zords, the sped up final battle is so hectic that we don't really get time to see the zords. Really hoping there'll be a sequel, because if not then there's just too little ranger time in a movie supposedly made for fans.   There is also the matter of American PC. Trini, the yellow ranger, can no longer be Asian, and the black ranger Zach cannot be black. Billy is now black, but still has the nerdy personality of white Billy cause we can't have a dancing and hip hop loving black ranger.   I couldn't care less about the race changes, I'd be perfectly happy with a Samoan Jason as long as he played the part of Jason..... I just wish the reasons the changes were made weren't so painfully obvious.

text: *Spolier alert* I saw the ratings on a few sites and I bet they were all done by people in their early 20's lol.. people that have no connection to the originals like we late 20's / 30's do. I loved every minute of it and even found little things sad that normally I wouldnt have done in films. Thats because of the emotional connections we have to the programmes. The opening scene sucked me in straight away with the yellow ranger and Zordon dying. I loved learning about these characters and their stories. We never got to see this side in the programmes.. they were just school kids and that's all we knew. Loved that they made us wait untill near the end of the film before they morphed to show the togetherness they had to have. That's what made the morphing scene so good.. "It's morphing time" - Love when Jason said that. Could have had more passion though üòÇ.  They connected the film to our day and age with an autistic character, bi / gay (?) character and someone that looks after his mum. Also showed Kimberly talking about the issues these days with people sending indecent pictures of themselves and Jason showed if you try hard there's always something else you can be good at going the american football to leading the Rangers. The ratings it received were way too harsh. Too much action and it would have been just a kids film. They made it for us. Bring on part 2....
